Use Spring as a small **plugin** system built on interfaces.

**Step 1 ŌĆö Define a stable interface.** Example: `PaymentProcessor` with `charge(Money m)`. Core code depends only on that interface, not on Stripe, PayPal, etc.

**Step 2 ŌĆö Inject all implementations as a list.** Spring can inject `List<PaymentProcessor>` with every `@Component` that implements the interface:
```java
@Service
public class PaymentRouter {
    private final List<PaymentProcessor> processors;
    public PaymentRouter(List<PaymentProcessor> processors) {
        this.processors = processors;
    }
}
```
A new JAR adds a new `@Component` ŌåÆ it appears in the list automatically.

**Step 3 ŌĆö Ordering.** Use `@Order` or `Ordered` if one processor should run before another.

**Step 4 ŌĆö Named choice.** Inject `Map<String, PaymentProcessor>` keyed by bean name if you pick by configuration string at runtime.

**Step 5 ŌĆö Optional modules.** Use `@ConditionalOnProperty("payment.stripe.enabled")` so beans only load when configured.

**Why it works:** Core stays closed for edits but open for new beans ŌĆö classic **strategy** / **plugin** style with **Spring DI** doing discovery.

**Verify:** Integration test with two fake processors in the list; third-party JAR test with **auto-configuration** import file if they ship Boot starters.
